<p><b>Albert Hofmann</b> (January 11, 1906 – April 29, 2008<sup id="cite_ref-maps_0-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-maps-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-telegraphobit_1-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-telegraphobit-1" title=""><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup>) was a <a href="/wiki/Switzerland" title="Switzerland">Swiss</a> scientist best known for having been the first to <a href="/wiki/Chemical_synthesis" title="Chemical synthesis">synthesize</a>, <a href="/wiki/Ingestion" title="Ingestion">ingest</a> and learn of the <a href="/wiki/Psychedelic" title="Psychedelic">psychedelic</a> effects of <a href="/wiki/Lysergic_acid_diethylamide" title="Lysergic acid diethylamide">lysergic acid diethylamide</a> (LSD). Hofmann authored more than 100 scientific articles and wrote a number of books, including <i>LSD: My Problem Child</i>. On January 11, 2006, Hofmann became a <a href="/wiki/Centenarian" title="Centenarian">centenarian</a>, and the occasion of his 100th birthday was the focus of an international symposium on <a href="/wiki/Lysergic_acid_diethylamide" title="Lysergic acid diethylamide">LSD</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-telegraphobit_1-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-telegraphobit-1" title=""><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<table id="toc" class="toc" summary="Contents">
